social_posts.post_text: I tell this story often, because in a really dark time, just a few words of encouragement from someone who I looked up to, changed my perspective. Bullies can’t cancel you. You just gotta get up, be strong and never give up on yourself. Thanks @haymawash - I won’t ever forget the strength our short convo gave me and how it changed everything during one of the most pivotal moments of my life and career. I don’t remember the words he said verbatim but this is how I interpreted the advice he gave me and that conversation. One thing’s for sure - I won’t ever forget how it made me feel.🙏🏽

Today marks the anniversary of losing a friend who was more like family, @branden_ruggiero. We all have those people who just get us; Branden was that person for me. From singing ‘Sweet Caroline’ at ballgames to hiking Cowles Mountain in San Diego, our shared moments were filled with dreams, laughter, and unwavering support.

Branden was a believer - in people, in connections, and in life’s grand possibilities. He loved bringing people together, like that unforgettable Friendsgiving where he insisted I do all the nerd social media things and film a YouTube challenge. He ordered my merch from Influences the day it launched, a testament to his faith in me, no matter what project I was working on.

We even made that playful pact: if neither of us found someone by 40, we’d marry each other. A platonic bond, deep and genuine.

The void left by Branden is immense, but his legacy continues to unite those who knew him. His positivity, his infectious smile, his dreamer’s heart – they all live on in our memories.

Whenever ‘Sweet Caroline’ plays, I feel Branden’s presence, singing along with me. Today, I honor him, grateful for the time we had and the lives he touched.

Branden, I hope you’re smiling from above, knowing you made this world a better place. Your melody lingers, and we will never forget you. #alwayswithb

Ever think you’re the BEST at what you do... until someone flips the mirror? 🪞

I always believed that if I wanted something done right, I had to do it myself. Perfection was my middle name. But then, I heard Maddy’s perspective on how I managed pressure.

She noticed I was a one-woman show. Operating in roles that would typically span across a 20-person company. While it felt like a badge of honor, Maddy’s insight showed me the cracks.

“Ari loved knowing that if she did it, it would be done exactly how she wanted it,” Maddy observed.

Her advice? ”Delegate, trust, and surround yourself with people that you can rely on.”

Hearing it out loud, I knew it was the truth. Delegation wasn’t my weakness; it was my missed strength.

Delegating isn’t about letting go of control. It’s about recognizing that true leadership involves trust.

It’s Labor Day so I thought it would be relevant to ask - Have you reflected on your delegation skills lately?

Ever wonder what it really takes to monetize on X (formerly Twitter)? The ins, the outs, the strategies… and the unexpected pitfalls?

In an X space chat hosted by @libertycappy, @mysteriouskat pulled back the curtain on her experience. Two things stood out:

	1.	Embrace Experimentation: Not every tweet…err post  is created equal. And when you’re continents apart from your core audience, like she is? You need to be agile. Adapt. Play around with scheduling. Even if it’s restrictive.
	2.	Thicken Your Skin: Got a post going viral? Great. But here’s the twist: Some comments might sting. Yet, every retort, every dig? It’s pushing your monetization up. There’s an art to transforming criticism into coins.

In the grand theater of online platforms, @mysteriouskat’s insights were a reminder: Monetizing on X isn’t just about tactics; it’s about mindset.

The game? It’s evolving. But with the right strategy, resilience, and a pinch of audacity? You can master it. Stay ahead. Stay in the game. 🚀

Cracking the 𝕏 Revenue Code: How I Got Paid and How YOU Can Too! (X, formally Twitter)

Recently, my bank account had a pleasant surprise - my very first payout from X (yeah, the platform you loved as Twitter)! Wondering how to grab a slice of that pie for yourself? Here’s the lowdown.

🚀 Ads Revenue Sharing: The Basics

X now shares revenue from organic impressions of ads displayed in replies to the killer content you post. They’re making big moves to help creators like us earn a living right here. Two options are on the table: Ads Revenue Sharing and Creator Subscriptions. Set them up independently, based on what suits your brand.

🌍 Global Availability

All creators, wherever you are, if you fit the bill, this is for you. But there are some boxes to tick…

📋 Eligibility Checklist

	1.	Platform Status: You need X Premium or to be a part of Verified Organizations.
	2.	Impressions Game: Gather a cool 5M organic impressions on your posts in the last 90 days.
	3.	Followers: Have a minimum of 500 followers riding your content wave.

🔗 What’s Next After Making The Cut?

	1.	Get Stripe Ready: This is where your money lands. Simple, secure, and global.
	2.	Rules of the Game: Stick to the Ads Revenue Share Terms. This includes the Creator Monetization Standards and the X Rules. A fair play ensures continued payouts.

🔔 Final Words

The fine print? X has the right to tweak or nix the program. They might also choose to include or exclude anyone. The game is theirs. But for now, it’s a win-win.

Go on, monetize that magic. And remember, the more value you bring to the table, the more you stand to gain. Dive in, and let’s change the game, together! 💼🚀🎯

Last December, I felt a shift. I’d always put my career first, but I decided it was time to put equal effort into my personal life. Dating apps were a grind, almost a second job, and I was close to calling it quits. Then, one Sunday after church, I found clarity and a bit of faith. I said a prayer. I asked God to bring someone kind and sincere into my life, someone who tries their best, just like I do.

That very night, I got an answer — a message from Kyle on Hinge from a few days before. It almost got lost in the shuffle, but there it was. Our connection was immediate. A few days later, we were at a concert together, the chemistry undeniable.

Almost a year has passed, and Kyle’s everything I could have hoped for and more. To all the women out there navigating the dating scene as the holidays draw near, let this give you a little hope. The genuine connection you’re looking for might just be a prayer away. My advice: let go of your ego and sincerely ask God for help finding the person you know you deserve. 🤍

As her former manager from 2019, here’s my take on Charli D’Amelio’s Walmart flop: when you live in a bubble, it’s bound to burst.  When I worked with her she starred in a successful 2019 Super Bowl ad. But since then, I’ve watched from afar at how easily talent can be boxed in by a ‘yes’ squad that’s only focused on the bottom line. Charli’s mistake? In my opinion - it’s a symptom of echo chamber management. 

The recent heat on Charli D’Amelio’s Walmart campaign is a stark reminder that a creator’s team is everything. Navigating fame’s waters needs more than just a business-minded crew; it requires a circle rich with diverse creator experiences.

As talent rises, it’s easy for their world to shrink, confined by a team’s protective barriers. This is done by design - because the team doesn’t want you to wander too far or to let too many people get in your ear. But it can become more self-serving for the agents than it is actual protection of the talent. Real growth—substantial growth—stems from rubbing shoulders with those who’ve walked the path. Has Charli spent enough time with the likes of @mrbeast , @collinskey or @mkbhd to learn the ropes? Not just for a quick collab, but to really glean wisdom?

In an industry where agents guard their roster jealously, true creator development can be stifled. It’s not just about keeping talent within reach; it’s about empowering them to build genuine connections and learn from the best. This isn’t just about avoiding PR misfires; it’s about evolving as a creator outside the echo chamber.

What do you guys think? How crucial is it for rising stars to branch out and learn from established creators? How can we foster an environment where growth and collaboration trump isolation and control?

(I’m not being critical of Charli as a person here btw, I thought she was lovely and enjoyed working with her.)
